# eCash allowance: the blast-radius bound on the AI's float.
#
# Read by arbiter/src/ecash.py (allowance_sats). The privacy gateway
# checks every fund_ecash against this cap BEFORE standing approvals:
#
#   refuse when  outstanding + requested > ecash_allowance_sats
#
# where outstanding = total funded - total successfully defunded
# (the ecash_ledger, maintained from gateway-visible events). The
# ordering is the point (design doc 07 §8): a standing approval - or
# a tired HITL "approve" - cannot widen the blast radius; raising
# the cap is an edit to this file at the directly-attached console,
# never an approval click.
#
# The arbiter ships with NO ecash.yaml: a missing file (or an
# unparseable value) reads as allowance 0, which refuses every fund.
# The float cannot exist until you write its bound here.
#
# Sizing discipline: this is petty cash. Worst-case AI behavior
# (burn, exfiltrate, gamble) and worst-case mint behavior (rug,
# freeze) both cost at most the outstanding float - size it as an
# amount whose TOTAL loss is acceptable as the cost of the autonomy
# experiment. There is no clawback on a bearer instrument: you can
# stop funding the float, but you cannot revoke it.
#
# What this does NOT bound (doc 07 §8): AI-direct spends inside the
# float are invisible by design, and tokens the AI receives from
# third parties are invisible AND unbounded - the allowance bounds
# operator loss, not AI wealth.
#
# Edit at the directly-attached arbiter console. Changes are
# captured by the arb-auditability snapshot tree under
# arbiter/config/ - the edit history IS the audit trail. The
# optional rate cap (ecash_funding_rate, doc 07 §8) lands with the
# timing-layer executor.
#
# Per design-docs/origin/07--2026-06-12-0916-ecash-extension.md §8
# and GLOSSARY 'eCash allowance'.

# ecash_allowance_sats: 50000
